objects.name: Mirai Malware
objects.description: Mirai is a malware that turns networked devices running Linux into remotely controlled bots that can be used as part of a botnet in large-scale network attacks. It primarily targets online consumer devices such as IP cameras and home routers. There are many forks and versions of Mirai each with differing capabilities. Many evolve rapidly to include new exploits for vulnerabilities found in the wild allowing the malware to spread on to new devices and increase the size of the botnet.

Mirai Variant MooBot Targeting D-Link Devices
objects.description:
In August 2022, Unit 42 researchers discovered attacks leveraging several D-Link vulnerabilities, including:

CVE-2015-2051: D-Link HNAP SOAPAction Header Command Execution Vulnerability
CVE-2018-6530: D-Link SOAP Interface Remote Code Execution Vulnerability
CVE-2022-26258: D-Link Remote Command Execution Vulnerability
CVE-2022-28958: D-Link Remote Command Execution Vulnerability

If the devices are compromised, they will be fully controlled by attackers, who can utilize those devices to conduct further attacks such as distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks. The exploit attempts captured by Unit 42 researchers leverage the aforementioned vulnerabilities to spread Moobot, a Mirai variant, which targets exposed networking devices running Linux. 
Please enter a description for this Campaign (markdown supported). 

Attacks were found targeted CVE-2015-2051 beginning on July 4, 2022.
